## Summary

KelvinClaw currently supports a single model provider (OpenAI via WASM plugin) with a single API key. As more providers are added, KelvinClaw needs auth profile management with failover, rate-limit detection, and cooldown policies — preventing outages when a key is rate-limited or billing-exhausted.

This issue is the final phase of the config security stack, building on Phases 1-3.

## Background: How OpenClaw Does It

OpenClaw supports multiple named auth profiles per provider with sophisticated failover:

```typescript
type AuthProfileConfig = {
    provider: string;                // "openai", "anthropic", etc.
    mode: "api_key" | "oauth" | "token";
    email?: string;
    displayName?: string;
};

type AuthConfig = {
    profiles?: Record<string, AuthProfileConfig>;
    order?: Record<string, string[]>;   // per-provider priority order
    cooldowns?: {
        billingBackoffHours?: number;              // hours to wait after billing error
        authPermanentBackoffMinutes?: number;      // minutes after auth failure
        overloadedProfileRotations?: number;       // how many profiles to try on overload
        rateLimitedProfileRotations?: number;      // how many profiles to try on rate limit
        errorBackoffMinutes?: number;
        rateLimitBackoffSeconds?: number;
    };
};
```

Key behaviors:
- **Profile rotation**: on rate limit or overload, try next profile in order
- **Backoff**: billing errors trigger hours-long cooldowns; rate limits trigger seconds-long cooldowns
- **Per-provider ordering**: each provider has its own priority list of profiles
- **Auth store**: persisted profile state (last error, cooldown until, usage stats)

Reference files: `src/config/types.auth.ts`, `src/agents/auth-profiles.ts`, `src/agents/auth-profiles/`

## What KelvinClaw Has Today

| Surface | Current State | Gap |
|---|---|---|
| Model provider auth | Single `OPENAI_API_KEY` env var | No multiple keys, no failover |
| Rate limit handling | None | Er
